Yes, this works. The downside is that there is always a substantial cost in switching current systems to integrate new technology. It will at least be a couple of years before we are ready to use hydrogen, because hydrogen has lower volumetric energy density compared to gasoline. Therefore, we need to find new ways to transport and store large amounts of hydrogen. In terms of economics, the reaction is already done on an industrial scale, to obtain hydrogen and carbon black or carbon monoxide. Currently, the hydrogen goes to the Haber-Bosch process (which also consumes hydrogen from the water-gas shift reaction). 

As of now, the process is more sustainable than using solar panels, as the manufacturing of solar panels requires a fairly substantial amount of energy and also leads to heavy metal pollution. Electrolysis is possibly one of the least efficient methods to produce hydrogen, as the electricity could have been consumed directly instead. Solar panels are also not quite good at producing hydrogen, since \~96500 Coulombs is 1 mole of electrons. Solar panels output electrons on the order of 10 amps, which is 10 coulombs per second. Thus, it will take approximately 9650 seconds  or 160 minutes to generate 1 mole of hydrogen gas, which corresponds to 1 gram of hydrogen. That is the amount of hydrogen in 9 grams of water, which corresponds to the amount of hydrogen in 4 grams of methane. The price of the solar panels will very quickly put the business of making hydrogen from solar out of business, especially when competing with the hydrocarbon industry. Perhaps, hydroelectric or wind might be somewhat okay sometime in the far future. 

&amp;#x200B;

In terms of economics, there is no way that renewable energy can compete with the carbon industry as of now, and probably for the next 30 years. The gravimetric and volumetric energy densities of renewable energy generation and storage just aren't there yet. We need at least another decade or two. The problem with batteries, is that batteries require a lot of resources to manufacture. Some day, when a dendrite-free rechargeable lithium metal battery hits the market, then we can begin to switch over.

&amp;#x200B;

Also, we have to look at the products of the reactions. For electrolysis, the byproduct is oxygen. Oxygen is very useful. However, oxygen is not very expensive, since there is a lot of oxygen around. In the hydrocarbon process, the high-purity carbon can be easily converted into high-purity graphene. Graphene has a far higher market price, because it is currently far harder to obtain and far more useful. A small amount of graphene in structural materials as a nano reinforcement can lead to a substantial improvement in mechanical properties. The ability to use less material will lead to big savings, in terms of manufacturing, which translates to less burden on the environment. The large-scale production of graphene at low cost will revolutionize nearly everything that relies on selling atoms and arrangements of atoms. The graphene market will soon explode, and we will soon be in the graphenic carbon age, where nearly every material will be enhanced by nano reinforcements.

